Now, let's see how our app works.
Open Postman, then make a WebSocket connection to localhost:8080/ws. Here I am using passing "ashis" as the username, in the header.Let's make another WebSocket request. Here I am using "barbie" as the username in the header.
Let's see the connected users using HTTP REST API.Now I am sending messages from the connection "ashis"But I'm not sending any messages from "barbie". So the connection is closed.Now, establish both connections again and send a message to a specific user. I am sending a message to "barbie".
Let's see if barbie received the message or not.
As you can see, barbie received the message successfully.How WebSockets work and how they differ from HTTPHow to establish and upgrade a connection using Gorilla WebSocketMessage types and how to read/write framesHow to detect idle clients using SetReadDeadline and close them cleanlyStoring and managing connections safely with sync.MutexConcurrency in Go each WebSocket runs in its own goroutine

In this tutorial, you’ll learn how to build an Asteroids game using Raylib-go, a lightweight library for game development.By the end, we will have a complete game with player movement controlled by the keyboard, shooting, collisions, and win/lose states and all in Go.


  Setting up your Go project
First, we need to set up our project and pull Raylib-go.We start by creating basic game loop functions to initialise the resources, update the state, draw it to the screen and deinitialise the resources.First, we set up a  function, which starts by deferring the  function. This will ensure that the  function runs at the end of the main() function.We use an init() function, which runs  the main() function. These two functions allow us to set up resources in memory and tear them down when we no longer need them.In the  function, we set up the Raylib window and set the FPS.We create a  function to use the new RayLib window to draw to the screen. We start the drawing with  and finish it with . We define our draw methods between those two calls. We set up an  function, which is called each frame. We will fill that out later.We simply clear the background with black and then draw a score in the top left corner.In the  function, we are called , which is a function that allows us to run our game loop until the Raylib window is closed or the ESC key is pressed.Now, we can run the code:What we should see is a black window with the score in the top left hand corner.The code for this section can be found on my GitHub RepoIt is a great start, though, we want to make this start look like our game. To start, we can add the space background.We load the image from a file and display it as our background:We start by declaring some global state, with the background text. Next, we need to load the image:We load the image from disk using the  call and assign it to the  variable.We need to make sure we are unloading it after the game, so we can do that in the  function.To do that, we run the  call.Now, we can draw the background to the screen:We have a bit of an issue, the image is 1536x1024px, when our window size is only 800x400px. To scale the image to our window, we need to use the  call.
This call takes the texture we want to draw, a rectangle within that texture and a destination texture on our window to draw it to. It also takes an Origin point, a Rotation and a Color, however, we are not using them.For the , which is used to select the part of the image to draw, we create a rectangle to select the whole image. For the , we select the whole screen in Raylib. We then call the  to draw the image to the screen.Let's check to see that our background is being shown:Beautiful, now it looks ready to start building our game on top of.The code for this section can be found on my GitHub Repo


  Create and draw the player
Next, we can set up the player for the game. This will be a ship that flies around and shoots at the asteroids.For this, I am going to use Kenney - Simple Space assets. There are some amazingly talented game artists around, and many of them provide assets for free.We can download the assets and put them into our  directory.Now, we load them into our game. We start by adding another texture to our game state:       texBackground rl.Texture2D
)
Then we need to load it in our  function:        // Load textures
        texBackground = rl.LoadTexture("resources/space_background.png")
Then unload it in our  function:        // Unload textures when the game closes
        rl.UnloadTexture(texBackground)
 }
Now that we have the texture loaded into memory, we can start to use it. However, as you may have spotted, the texture is a spritemap, made up of an 8x6 grid of sprites. We want to use one of them for our ship.Luckily, we already saw a function that would allow us to select a section of the texture and draw it to the screen. We can use the  to take a smaller section of the original image and then draw that for us.Let's start by defining our source selection rectangle. We will also create a  to track how large we want the image.In the , we add the :    screenWidth  = 800
    screenHeight = 400
)
Now, we define our source selection rectangle for the ship:    texTiles      rl.Texture2D
    texBackground rl.Texture2D
)
Then, in the  function, we can define the sprite source:    texTiles = rl.LoadTexture("resources/tilesheet.png")
    texBackground = rl.LoadTexture("resources/space_background.png")
}
We select the ship on the 3rd row (Index 2) on the 1st position (Index 0). As the tiles on the map are  wide and high. We use that variable to calculate where in the tilemap we want to select. You can see from the image below how we have picked the ship we want.Now we have our selection, we need to draw it on the screen. To make these easier, we create a  struct to hold all the player related behaviours.We create the  structure with Vectors for the ,  and . We have some floats for  and , which we use to move the sprite. Finally, we have a boolean for boosting.Now we can draw the sprite to the screen:func (p *Player) Draw() {
    destTexture := rl.Rectangle{X: p.position.X, Y: p.position.Y, Width: p.size.X, Height: p.size.Y}
    rl.DrawTexturePro(
        texTiles,
        spriteRec,
        destTexture,
        rl.Vector2{X: p.size.X / 2, Y: p.size.Y / 2},
        p.rotation,
        rl.White,
    )
}
We define a , similar to the way we did the background; however, instead of covering the whole screen, we want the sprite to appear in the centre of the screen.We need to create the new player when we start the game. For this, we create a variable in the state and a little helper function to do all the initialisation:    texTiles      rl.Texture2D
    texBackground rl.Texture2D
    spriteRec     rl.Rectangle
)
We need to add the new initialisation of the game to the  function:...
    texBackground = rl.LoadTexture("resources/space_background.png")
    spriteRec = rl.Rectangle{X: tileSize * 0, Y: tileSize * 2, Width: tileSize, Height: tileSize}
}
Now we have a  object, we need to add it to the  in the main game loop:...
    rl.DrawTexturePro(texBackground, bgSource, bgDest, rl.Vector2{X: 0, Y: 0}, 0, rl.White)
    // Draw the score to the screen
    rl.DrawText("Score 0", 10, 10, 20, rl.Gray)
...
Looks like that is all we need to draw the player, let's give it a shot and see if it works:We should see our background image, and our new sprite drawn into the window in the middle of the screen:We are successfully using the tilemap and drawing a sprite to the screen.The code for this section can be found on my GitHub Repo


  Implementing player movement
Next, we start to give the game some life, with some movement. We want to move the player using the keyboard. So we will need to set up some code to manage the keyboard inputs and manipulate our sprite accordingly.Let's start by creating some constants for the speed of the player and the rotation speed. This allows us to tweak it later.    screenWidth   = 800
    screenHeight  = 400
    tileSize      = 64
)
Now we have our variables, we can create an  method on our  struct to move the player when the keyboard is used:We start by capturing the  and  events, then rotate the ship based on the direction. We capture  and  for acceleration.To make it a little more realistic, the ship has no friction (Just like space!), so we need to actively decelerate to slow down.We use the  to translate our  into a vector, and we use that vector to change the direction of the ship with the  attribute. We then add the  and the  to the position to move the ship in that direction.Finally, we use the  function to wrap the position so our ship is not lost in space as soon as we leave the screen.We need to create our  function:And our  function:Finally, we can replace our  method with the main game loop to move the ship each frame:Let's run  to see if we can move the ship.Our player is moving based on the keypresses from the arrow keys.The code for this section can be found on my GitHub RepoTo give the game a little moe realism, let's add a boost to the little ship, so it looks like that is how the ship is moving.We already have the  attribute on the  struct. Let's use that. We will select another sprite from the tilemap and draw it only when we are boosting.    texTiles      rl.Texture2D
    texBackground rl.Texture2D
    spriteRec     rl.Rectangle
    player        Player
)
We create a new selection rectangle from the tilemap in the global game state.        texBackground = rl.LoadTexture("resources/space_background.png")
        spriteRec = rl.Rectangle{X: tileSize * 0, Y: tileSize * 2, Width: tileSize, Height: tileSize}
        initGame()
We then select the tile we want to use. We want to use the yellow thrust pattern, which makes it look like the ship is activating its engine. func (p *Player) Draw() {
        destTexture := rl.Rectangle{X: p.position.X, Y: p.position.Y, Width: p.size.X, Height: p.size.Y}
        rl.DrawTexturePro(
We update the  method on the  struct to check if we are boosting; if we are, draw the boost sprite under the ship sprite.        if rl.IsKeyDown(rl.KeyRight) {
                player.rotation += rotationSpeed
        }
        // Accelerate the player with up
        if rl.IsKeyDown(rl.KeyUp) {
            if player.acceleration < 0.9 {
                player.acceleration += 0.1
            }
        }
Finally, we add a toggle on the acceleration action so  is true when accelerating and defaults to false when we are not.Let's run the game with It now looks like our ship is using its engines to speed up!The code for this section can be found on my GitHub RepoNow that we have the player boosting and moving, we need to add the asteroids to the scene, so the player has something to dodge and shoot.We start by following the same sprite selection pattern as before. We create a rectangle to select and we initialise it.We also need a place to store the asteroids:    texTiles      rl.Texture2D
    texBackground rl.Texture2D
    spriteRec     rl.Rectangle
    boostRec      rl.Rectangle
    player        Player
)
We create an  to select the sprite and an  slice to store them in.    screenWidth      = 800
    screenHeight     = 400
    tileSize         = 64
    rotationSpeed    = 2.0
    playerSpeed      = 6.0
)
We also add a constant for how many asteroids we want to spawn in to start with.In the classic Asteroids manner, we are going to start with large asteroids. When we shoot them, they will break apart and spawn smaller asteroids. To do this, we need a way to track the size of the asteroid. We can use an enum for this, though. Go does not have an enum construct; we can use the  to create one:Here, we create a new type  and provide it with three named options ,  and . Under the hood, these are s. However, we can now use them to make our code easier to read.Now to create the :We start with the , which contains the ,  and  vectors. We have the new  to determine how big to draw the sprite.We create the  method to draw the sprite onto the screen.In the  method, we add the  to the  to move the asteroid and ensure that our asteroids wrap around the screen.Now that we have our Asteroid defined, we can start to create some when the game initialises. To do this, we create a helper function to generate a Large Asteroid in a random place, with a random speed and direction.This function uses the  function to generate a number between  and , which represent different sides of the screen. Then it creates a vector with a random speed. Finally, it passes it to another helper function to create the Asteroid.This function takes in a size and its vectors and creates an Asteroid of that size at the vectors. The helper function can be reused later when we want to create more asteroids.Finally, we need to update the  function to create our initial set of asteroids.    // Create the player
    player = Player{
We will also need to define our selection rectangle in the  function, for the asset in the tile map:    // Sprites for the ship and it boost
    spriteRec = rl.Rectangle{X: tileSize * 0, Y: tileSize * 2, Width: tileSize, Height: tileSize}
    boostRec = rl.Rectangle{X: tileSize * 7, Y: tileSize * 5, Width: tileSize, Height: tileSize}
